A jet of flames erupted from Thassalin's jaws as the colossal Thraki set a specific part of the forest on fire, then circled above, observing for a moment. Strangely, as he had slowed down, the odd noises of cries behind him had stopped. Thassalin had forgotten that he had passengers on his back.
Come on, Tenuk, you've already turned into a Thraki before!
"My flight is very different. I don't get suddenly lifted by a huge pink dragon!"
"It's not so unpleasant, is it, Kayel?"
Kayel clearly disagreed with Nyssi; he seemed less black than usual and had planted his claws into Thassalin's back so deeply that he had drawn blood from the Thraki, but apparently, he didn't care. That said, Thassalin had realized he had terrified his new friends and had found a clearing to land in.
"MY APOLOGIES, I SNIFFED A SMELL. I HAD TO CHECK."
"You had to drag us here with you?" Tenuk said as he slid down Thassalin's back along his tail. "And we left Retvik behind! We abandoned our big and strong fighter! How is he going to join us?"
"He'll find a way," retorted Nissy. "Retvik is slow, but not stupid."
"Okay, but does Retvik know how to drive?"
Nissy blinked and turned back to Tenuk. "Of course he knows how to drive."
"Have you ever seen Retvik driving a vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I've never seen him drive anything like Kayel's cute little car either. And if he started coming to work by car, it's only because YOU drive us there. He just has that bike."
A burst of laughter interrupted them. Thassalin was suddenly hilarious, and no one understood what was making him laugh. It took him a little too long to regain his composure.
"I'M SORRY, BUT I IMAGINED YOUR TALL FRIEND IN ARMOR ON A MINIATURE BIKE MEANT FOR CHILDREN TEMTHAN. IT WAS SO FUNNY! I WOULD HAVE LIKED TO BE TALENTED IN TELEPATHY. THAT WAS A PRECIOUS THOUGHT! ONE I CAN'T SHARE!"
Kayel snickered, imagining what Thassalin was thinking. "Yes, that's just it. But what did you pick up and why did you take off so quickly?"
Thassalin grumbled, took off, and disappeared briefly before returning and dropping a carcass in front of Nyssi. It was an Orothrack, a golden and white draconic creature, very rare. But it was missing its head. "ANOTHER DEATH. I HEAR THEIR WAILS. I FEEL THEIR BLOOD. I AM PROGRAMMED TO PROTECT AND HUNT. AS YISINI DEMANDS. THE CREATURES ARE NEAR."
The powerful Thraki suddenly froze. Nyssi and Kayel did too, their attention drawn to a break in the clearing. Something large and black was staring at them, hissing. Whatever it was, this thing opened two colossal pairs of wings and charged straight at Thassalin, unbothered by the three smaller beings in its path. Kayel and Tenuk just managed to take cover, but Nyssi was dragged along and almost thrown onto Thassalin.
Thassalin reacted to the attack by grabbing Nyssi and hurling her onto his back with his extraordinarily long and dexterous tail before taking off. The two-winged black creature quickly gave chase.
Kayel exhaled as he drew the rifle from his back, then opened a pouch containing a ammunition belt. He slung it over his shoulder to be able to access it easily, but quickly realized that Nyssi, the Thraki, and the monster were no longer visible.
"Hey Tenuk, would you mind turning into something that can fly?" asked Kayel.
"Do you want to chase them?"
"Yes, of course!"
"But... one of them is a giant monster!"
"And what if I do? I have an ultra-powerful gun in my hands right now, ready to use. I only need to see it to shoot it."
Tenuk hesitated, then stepped back to make some space. In a faint, slightly pained growl, his body unfolded, his fur was replaced by scales, and his arms transformed into wings. He quickly reverted to his normal light blue Thraki form, but his eyes remained red.
"Climb."
Having regained a more normal Thraki appearance, Tenuk now had his back covered in scale plates, but a pair of spines had also grown on it, handy for Kayel to grip. Tenuk needed a bit of time to take off, but once in the air, he quickly oriented himself and attempted to pursue.
However, Tenuk and Kayel quickly realized they were not alone. A second dark creature emerged from below, and Tenuk barely managed to avoid it.
I suppose that's the other big scary monster that worried Lanex? Kayel furrowed his brows while trying to shoot the second creature, missed his target, and quickly reloaded his weapon.
Tenuk didn't react. He was too focused on his flight toward Nyssi and Thassalin, despite the other creature pursuing them. Kayel awkwardly spun around to face the monster. The fact that it was chasing them was a blessing for Kayel, as it made it easier for him to aim and shoot. Two shots passed through the creature's upper wings, which howled in pain and disappeared again under the trees. Kayel didn't know if it was still following them, but it certainly wouldn't be able to catch up.
Further away, Nyssi was desperately clinging on, while Thassalin flew in circles, firing bursts of flames at the blackened monster. Although the creature was clearly injured, it seemed furious and determined to fight, and the fireballs didn't seem to have the intended effect. When Thassalin straightened up, Nyssi took the opportunity to draw her weapon, a reliable rifle. It was certainly not intended for this kind of situation, but a volley of shots would surely at least deter the black beast, right?
